Statistics and data science

“The unique strength of the statistics discipline is the extent of its relevance to the whole of the natural and social sciences.”

Peter Diggle, Statistics: a data science for the 21st century

“I do think it would be fair to consider statistics as a subset of data science. The tech industry has always had to deal with databases and coding The statistical part of data science is more of an option.”

Andrew Gelman, Columbia University (statmodeling.stat.columbia.edu)

“If data science is a close relation of statistics, its increasing popularity must surely present us [statisticians] with an opportunity What can we offer? Crucially, we can assert that uncertainty is ubiquitous and that probability is the correct way to deal with uncertainty. We understand the uncertainty in our data by building stochastic models, and in our conclusions by probabilistic inference.”

Peter Diggle, Statistics: a data science for the 21st century

Motivating examples

I will always motivate any difficult theory in this module using examples based on real research. I strongly believe that giving theory without context is just a poor method of teaching.

Medical examples are particularly inspiring and will be common throughout this module.

Photograph of an aortic valve replacement form the MiniStern clinical trial (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30075959). Statistical analysis of this trial was carried out here in Leeds, at the Clinical Trials Research Unit.

Motivating examples

  • GlobularClusters, the number of globular star clusters orbiting the the core of the galaxy.
  • BlackHoleMass, the mass of the black hole at the centre of the galaxy.
  • Distance, the distance from Earth in light-years.
  • Vdispersion, how fast objects in the galaxy are moving relative to each other.
  • Eradius, the radius at which half of the total light of the galaxy is emitted.
  • Type: Elliptical, Spiral or Lenticular.

The Milky Way galaxy. Credit: ESA/Hubble, NASA, L Calcada, M Kormesser.

Coursework

Your coursework is based on data from the Radford/FGCU Serial Killer database.

But, again, why do we care about this? Isnt this a job for a criminologist?

It has been noted that, generally, research on serial killers has limited credibility and relies too heavily on case studies and descriptive statistics.Gurian EA. 2017. Reframing serial murder within empirical research. International Journal of Offender Therapy and Comparative Criminology 61(5).

Recently published research on serial killersSimkin MV, Roychowdhury VP. 2014. Stochastic modeling of a serial killer. Journal of Theoretical Biology 355. has received harsh criticism for poor use of statistics and for its attempt to link epilepsy to criminal behaviour.

load("killersandmotives.Rdata")
x = 16   # a number that I will allocate to you
createsample(x)   # this function takes a unique sample of killers for you to analyse
